The seventh Global Environment Outlook of the United Nations Environment Programme has been published without a government-approved Summary for Policymakers. As assessment co-chairs and authors involved in the Summary for Policymakers approval process, we propose safeguards to keep the science timely and intact when the political process stalls.In multilateral science–policy processes, a Summary for Policymakers (SPM) provides a concise overview of key findings from major scientific assessments. Drafted by scientists, reviewed by experts and governments, and negotiated line-by-line to reach consensus, it distils thousands of pages of research into a few dozen pages for decision makers. An SPM presents findings in an accessible, policy-relevant form and is considered the main output of such assessments. These summaries are not policy prescriptive and do not create legal obligations1. They are standard in the assessment reports of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), Intergovernmental Science-Policy Platform on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES), and the United Nations Environment Programme’s (UNEP’s) Global Environment Outlooks (GEOs).



